04305nam a22005175i 9780804776523DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047765237 a10.1515/97808047765232doi  a(DE-B1597)563776  a(OCoLC)1198932078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS135.C96bM665 2011eb 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a943.72/0049242221 aMiller, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRabbis and Revolution :bThe Jews of Moravia in the Age of Emancipation /cMichael Miller. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (480 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Jewish History and C00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Language, Place Names, and Currency -- tIntroduction -- tOne. From Přemyslids to Habsburgs -- tTwo. Rabbinic Enlightenment -- tThree. Nehemias Trebitsch and the Decline of the Moravian Chief Rabbinate, 1832-1842 -- tFour. Locking Antlers -- tFive. Conflict and Revolution -- tSix. On the Altar of Freedom -- tSeven. Emancipation and Its Aftershocks -- tEight. Drifting Rabbis, Shifting Centers, and the Burgeoning Czech-German Conflict -- tAppendix 1. Moravia's Fifty-Two Jewish Communities, 1798-1848 -- tAppendix 2. Moravian Jewish Communities Established After 1848 -- tAppendix 3. Jewish Population in Moravia and Austrian Silesia, 1754-1921 -- tAbbreviations Used Only in Notes and Bibliography -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Habsburg province of Moravia straddled a complicated linguistic, cultural, and national space, where German, Slavic, and Jewish spheres overlapped, intermingled, and sometimes clashed. Situated in the heart of Central Europe, Moravia was exposed to major Jewish movements from the East and West, including Haskalah (Jewish enlightenment), Hasidism, and religious reform. Moravia's rooted and thriving rabbinic culture helped moderate these movements and, in the case of Hasidism, keep it at bay. During the Revolution of 1848, Moravia's Jews took an active part in the prolonged and ultimately successful struggle for Jewish emancipation in the Habsburg lands. The revolution ushered in a new age of freedom, but it also precipitated demographic, financial, and social transformations, disrupting entrenched patterns that had characterized Moravian Jewish life since the Middle Ages. These changes emerged precisely when the Czech-German conflict began to dominate public life, throwing Moravia's Jews into the middle of the increasingly virulent nationality conflict. For some, a cautious embrace of Zionism represented a way out of this conflict, but it also represented a continuation of Moravian Jewry's distinctive role as mediator-and often tamer-of the major ideological movements that pervaded Central Europe in the Age of Emancipation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aJewszCzech RepubliczMoraviaxHistoryy19th century. 0aJudaismzCzech RepubliczMoraviaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804776523zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804776523423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804776523.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles